This dataset contains web scraped data on products and sales from Sephora, a beauty store.

Target variable: love = The number of people that love a product.

No missing values were present in our categorical predictors.

Convert numeric columns back to numbers

sephora$love <- as.numeric(sephora$love)
v_numeric <- c(
  "price","value_price"
)
for(j in v_numeric) sephora[,j] <- as.numeric(
  x = sephora[,j]
)

Visualizing target variable

sephora$Bin <- cut_number(  
  x = sephora$love,
  n = 3,
  closed = "left"
)

sephora %>%
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(love)) %>%  
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = love,fill = Bin) +
  geom_histogram(bins=9000) +
  theme_bw() +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,50000)) +
  labs(
    title = "Histogram of love",
    subtitle = "love = the number of people that love a product"
  )

As we can see, our data is heavily right skewed.

Transforming target variable

# Calculates the YeoJohnson transform
preProcess_love <- caret::preProcess(
  x = sephora %>% dplyr::select(love),
  method = "YeoJohnson"
)

# Performs the YeoJohnson transform on the target variable
sephora$YJ_love <- predict(
  object= preProcess_love,
  newdata = sephora
)$love


sephora %>%
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(love)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = YJ_love,fill = Bin) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100) +
  theme_bw() +
  #coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,50000))+
  labs(
    title = "Histogram of transformed love"
  )

Now our data is more symmetric compared to before.

Visualize target variable by categorical predictors

v_wilcox.test <- sapply(
  X = names(categorical),
  FUN = function(j) mean(as.vector(pairwise.wilcox.test(
    x = sephora$love[!is.na(sephora$love)],
    g = sephora[!is.na(sephora$love),j]
  )$p.value),na.rm = TRUE)
)
v_wilcox.test <- sort( # Ranks the predictors by the Wilcox test's p value
  x = v_wilcox.test
)


library(ggplot2)
for(j in names(v_wilcox.test)){
  sephora_plot <- sephora[,c("love",j)] %>%
    dplyr::group_by_(j) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(median_love = median(love,na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    dplyr::ungroup()
  
  p <- ggplot(sephora_plot) + 
    aes_string(x = j) + 
    aes(y = love,fill = median_love) +
    geom_boxplot(color = "grey50") +
    coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100000)) +
    theme_bw() +
    labs(
      title = paste0("Box plots of love by ",j),
      subtitle = "Boxes with very different vertical positions give better predictors"
    )
  plot(p)
}

From our plots, MarkgetingFlags has the most impact followed by Rating based on Wilcoxon-signed-rank test p values. Category and Brand did not provide much information since there are so many levels.

Capping extreme numeric values to prevents outliers from pulling model away from the rest of the data

# Capping extreme values outside of the 99 percentile to the highest capped value at 99 percentile.
for(j in v_numeric){
  v_cutoffs <- quantile(
    x = sephora[,j],
    probs = c(
      0.01,0.99
    ),
    na.rm = TRUE
  )
  sephora[sephora[,j] < v_cutoffs[1] & !is.na(sephora[,j] < v_cutoffs[1]),j] <- v_cutoffs[1]
  sephora[v_cutoffs[2] < sephora[,j] & !is.na(v_cutoffs[2] < sephora[,j]),j] <- v_cutoffs[2]
}

Visualizing the target variable by numeric predictors

v_cor <- sapply(
  X = v_numeric,
  FUN = function(j) cor(
    x = sephora[,j],
    y = sephora$YJ_love,
    method = "spearman",
    use = "pairwise.complete.obs"
  )
)


v_cor <- v_cor[order( # orders the correlation from largest absolute value to smallest
  x = abs(
    x = v_cor
  ),
  decreasing = TRUE
)]


for(j in names(v_cor)){
  sephora_plot <- sephora[,c("YJ_love","Bin",j)]
  p <- ggplot(sephora_plot[complete.cases(sephora_plot),]) +
    aes_string(x = j) +
    aes(y = YJ_love) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = Bin)) + 
    geom_smooth(color = "black",se = FALSE,method = "loess") + # loess method was used b/c linear regression was too rigid
    theme_bw() + 
    labs(
      title = paste0("Scatter plot of sale price by ",j),
      subtitle = paste0("Spearman correlation: ",round(v_cor[j],2),"\nEach color has 33% of the points."),
      caption = "Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques"
    )
  plot(p)
}
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Based on the plots and spearman correlation coefficient, it appears that neither of our numeric predictors have a strong correlation to our target variable. It also appears that these 2 predictor variables might be very similar and could lead to colinearity later on.

sapply(
  X = sephora,
  FUN = function(x) sum(is.na(x))
)

No missing values in our numeric predictor variables either.

Binning categorical predictor variables by conditional means

for(j in names(categorical)){
  M_YJ_love <- sephora %>%
    dplyr::select_(j,"YJ_love") %>%
    dplyr::mutate_(j = as.character(j)) %>%
    dplyr::group_by_(j) %>%
    dplyr::summarise(YJ_love = mean(YJ_love,na.rm = TRUE),n = dplyr::n()) %>%
    dplyr::ungroup() %>%
    dplyr::mutate(proportion = n/sum(n)) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(YJ_love) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(cumsum_ascending = cumsum(proportion)) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(dplyr::desc(cumsum_ascending)) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(cumsum_descending = 1 - cumsum(proportion)) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(cumsum_ascending) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(mean_cumsum = (cumsum_ascending + cumsum_descending)/2) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(mean_cumsum) %>%
    as.data.frame()
  v_j <- levels(M_YJ_love[,j])[M_YJ_love$mean_cumsum >= 0.5]
  sephora[,j] <- as.numeric(
    x = sephora[,j] %in% M_YJ_love[M_YJ_love$mean_cumsum >= 0.5,j]
  )
  print(
    x = "---------------------------------------------------------------------"
  )
  print(
    x = j
  )
  print(knitr::kable(
    M_YJ_love
  ))
}
